{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486956","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486956"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:51:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:51:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"217"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"217","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/217"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.02,0.32,0.37,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"217"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44865"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"217","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/217"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"217"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29752"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1749"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"},{"type":"tags","id":"9161"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11593"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16173"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44865"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA healthy 27-year-old man presents with pain in his right groin which occurred after lifting a heavy weight at work. He has not noticed any swelling in this region. No abnormality can be found on examination of his groins, other than some tenderness in the region of the pubic tubercle. An ultrasound examination is performed and the report reads:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u0027There is a 1cm defect at the deep inguinal ring, with herniation of fat into the inguinal canal when the patient coughs...\u0027\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Repeat ultrasound in six months","CT groin","Reassurance alone","Laparoscopic hernia repair","Open hernia repair"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pain that the patient experienced is almost certainly musculoskeletal in origin, especially with the finding of the area of tenderness. With a normal physical examination that does not find any clinically apparent inguinal hernia, all the patient needs is \u003Cstrong\u003Ereassurance\u003C/strong\u003E and the explanation that his pain will settle on its own accord. The probable correct diagnosis is osteitis pubis. He should be advised that further heavy lifting or straining might aggravate things. Arrangements can be made to review the patient if the pain does not settle. This type of injury is often referred to as a sportsman\u0027s hernia.\u0027\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst an ultrasound examination is a very commonly performed examination in the assessment of patients with groin pain, the report should always be interpreted with reference to the clinical picture. In this case there is no clinical evidence of a hernia and the report is misleading.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe deep inguinal ring has a normal diameter of 2 cm, so the report of a \u0027 1 cm defect\u0027 is of no clinical significance. Likewise herniation of some fat into the canal is very unlikely to be of clinical relevance. Unfortunately this scenario is all too common, with these patients being referred for a surgical opinion and consideration of a \u0027hernia repair.\u0027 Even if this patient was found to have a hernia, recent studies have shown that small, minimally symptomatic, first occurrence hernias do not necessarily require repair; instead, they suggest counselling the patient on red-flag symptoms suggestive of incarceration and strangulation, with advice to seek prompt evaluation in these instances.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Groin \u0027hernias\u0027 that are not clinically evident and only found on imaging are unlikely to be of any clinical significance."],"references":["LeBlanc, K, LeBlanc, LL \u0026 LeBlanc, KA 2013, \u2018Inguinal Hernias: Diagnosis and Management\u2019, American Family Physician, vol. 87, no. 12, pp. 844\u2013848."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29752"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"217"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29752","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29752"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-06T11:10:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-29T10:12:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"217"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44865"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their deg